 gummy.
I know what you're probably thinking...creatine?! Me too. I had the same re=
action when my brother Dan first texted me about starting the business. I a=
lways associated creatine with bodybuilders and high school football player=
s and bucketed it with =E2=80=9Csteroids.=E2=80=9D
But Dan did his homework and showed me the research, and it turns out that =
creatine is one of the safest and most effective general performance supple=
ments on the market. Andrew Huberman is on the record as taking 5 grams per=
 day. Peter Attia called it "the supplement he feels most confident recomme=
nding to patients." The guys who know the most about this stuff view creati=
ne as a table stakes supplement. Here's why:
Safe: The FDA marked creatine monohydrate as "generally recognized as safe"=
 in 2020.=20
Effective: If you've ever taken creatine before, this one is obvious and it=
's what differentiates it from most other supplements: it works.
Beneficial: increases strength, builds muscle, improves recovery. Recent re=
search also indicates that creatine may benefit memory and general cognitiv=
e performance.
I now take 5 gummies (5g) per day to boost my recovery and overall performa=
nce -- it's part of my morning routine now that I=E2=80=99m running more an=
d I=E2=80=99m old. But I=E2=80=99m biased -- my brother started the company=
 and I'm an investor. Try it out for yourself, 30% off:=20
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=C2=A0
Happy Tuesday! I hope those of you in the US had a great long weekend.=C2=
=A0
This is an essay I=E2=80=99ve wanted to write for a long time, since I expe=
rienced what happens to a company when the differentiation disappears. I=E2=
=80=99m glad I waited. It=E2=80=99s more relevant now than ever.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=C2=A0
Differentiation
Being different beats being better, and differentiation=E2=80=99s lead is o=
nly going to widen from here.
If the last era rewarded conformity and competition, the next one will rewa=
rd differentiation and cooperation.=C2=A0
Quickly, what is differentiation? It=E2=80=99s a big strategy word that you=
 hear a lot. It=E2=80=99s one of Michael Porter=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cgeneric =
strategies,=E2=80=9D along with cost leadership and focus. These strategies=
 are =E2=80=9Cgeneric=E2=80=9D because they can be applied to any type of b=
usiness, big or small, complex or simple. In this context, differentiation =
means a company=E2=80=99s efforts to distinguish its products or services f=
rom competitors=E2=80=99 in customers=E2=80=99 minds in order to charge hig=
her prices and generate higher profits. Instead of competing on cost, you c=
ompete on convincing customers that there=E2=80=99s nothing else just like =
you out there.
That definition is part of what I=E2=80=99m talking about, but the differen=
tiation we=E2=80=99ll cover today is more multifaceted than that, it applie=
s beyond running a company, and it=E2=80=99s deeper than convincing custome=
rs. The differentiation I=E2=80=99m talking about is doing something that n=
o one else is doing, and that it=E2=80=99s possible no one else can.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ll start to explain why I value differentiation so highly through=
 three personal stories, and then I=E2=80=99ll explain why I=E2=80=99m fina=
lly writing it now, and why I think differentiation will only get more impo=
rtant from here.=C2=A0
Ultimately, real differentiation is the only defensible moat left.=C2=A0
Three Stories
Story 1: Pumpkins=C2=A0
My Sixth Grade teacher, Mr. Clarke, had a superpower, something that he was=
 better at than anyone in the entire world.=C2=A0
Of course, a lot of sixth graders think that their teachers are the smartes=
t, or funniest, or strongest, or whateverest in the world. They don=E2=80=
=99t know many grownups. But I had proof in the form of two cold, hard Guin=
ness World Records.=C2=A0
