Story 2: Breather
Now, let me tell you my Breather story. This one=E2=80=99s about what happe=
ns when differentiation dies.
Before Not Boring, I worked at a startup called Breather. Breather was Rube=
 Goldbergian in its operational complexity.=C2=A0
We leased office spaces, did construction, furnished them, rented them out =
through an app for as little as 30 minutes, gave customers access via ever-=
changing door codes, priced them dynamically based on demand, and cleaned a=
nd refreshed them after every reservation. It was weird and hard.=C2=A0
No one in their right mind would run a business like Breather, but that was=
 the advantage. Breather=E2=80=99s weirdness was beautiful. Breather was di=
fferentiated, and that came with a bunch of benefits:=C2=A0
Booking a Breather, accessing an office with your phone, and getting a quie=
t space to yourself in the city was a novel, magical experience that people=
 told their friends about.=C2=A0
We built direct relationships with our customers.=C2=A0
We had pricing power.=C2=A0
We attracted an exceptional team to do a really hard thing.=C2=A0
And as hard as it was, our employee retention was high. It was fun coming t=
o work.=C2=A0
There was just one problem: our gross margins were shit. Different doesn=E2=
=80=99t necessarily mean good. Four years in, we had expanded our real esta=
te portfolio too quickly, had a bunch of spaces that sat empty day after da=
y, and those spaces dragged our portfolio-wide gross margins to something l=
ike -25%. Not good!=C2=A0
Something needed to change, so one Christmas break, Ben Rollert [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/104b7acc-b218-43ed-9636-f2114c7ce206?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (now the CEO of Compose=
r [ https://substack.com/redirect/35d52d7d-3005-4c1f-8e7f-48d96855e26b?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]) and I wor=
ked on a plan. WeWork was the 800 lb gorilla, offering monthly workspaces f=
or individuals and small teams. Knotel was the brash newcomer, spending rec=
klessly on a monthly office product that felt like a real office instead of=
 a glass box. Where did Breather fit in?=C2=A0
The plan we came up with was even more operationally complex and weirder th=
an our original model. It leveraged on our strengths (and our biggest weakn=
ess):=C2=A0
The app and short bookings as top-of-funnel=C2=A0
The capability our data science and real estate teams had built up in under=
writing and pricing spaces because we had more granular, real-time data tha=
n anyone else
The fact that we already did the hardest thing, short on-demand bookings
The fact that we had too much supply
We would use dynamic pricing and fill-rate projections to put a monthly pri=
ce on all of our spaces, and let market dynamics work their magic. Our less=
 popular spaces could be had for cheaper than competitors=E2=80=99 because =
they were going to lose us money anyway, and when they were filled by the m=
onth, demand got pushed to more popular spaces, turbo-charging their margin=
s. Our more popular spaces could be rented at above-market prices, locking =
in margins and once again redistributing demand to other hourly spaces. On =
top of the monthly product, we created a richer offering than WeWork or Kno=
tel could that we viewed as a living, breathing network of spaces that coul=
d fill the different needs customers had at different times.
All of this was really complex =E2=80=93 to explain to customers, for one t=
hing, but even just to execute. We essentially bolted a second business ont=
o the first, and needed to change the way we did practically everything, la=
yering complexity on complexity.=C2=A0
It was really fucking hard, but it was exhilirating. The company rallied be=
hind the evolution. There were a lot of late nights and gong rings. We were=
 doing something that no one else was doing. The difficulty was worth it, b=
ecause the result was a differentiated product.=C2=A0
And it worked! In less than six months, our portfolio-wide margins across o=
ur ten markets, as Biggie would say, went from negative to positive. Specif=
ically, we went from -25% gross margins to +25% gross margins. If different=
iation is ultimately expressed in higher profits, our differentiation was f=
