take in vivid and varied adventures to build up a set of experiences that i=
s unique to you. Run away from the areas in which you are average and towar=
ds those where you might be special. Start a company because the world need=
s it, and because if you don=E2=80=99t start that specific company, no one =
else will.
You don=E2=80=99t need to be the world=E2=80=99s best brain surgeon; you mi=
ght be the world=E2=80=99s fastest pumpkin carver. And when you find those =
areas where your curiosity, skills, and personality meet, lean in so hard t=
hat you create a Personal Monopoly no human or machine can touch.=C2=A0
The world will be a richer, more colorful place when more people are freed =
up to learn, create, and build novel things that only they can. This might =
be technology=E2=80=99s greatest gift to humanity. By making the competitio=
n to be better at someone else=E2=80=99s game practically futile, it frees =
us up to play different games.=C2=A0
