on></figure></div><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height:=
 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The Personal Monopoly is the intersection=
 of the things you&#8217;re good at, the things you&#8217;re curious about,=
 and your own personality. As </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redire=
ct/c672c42b-2cb7-481d-abc0-e7d19580d21c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-dec=
oration: underline;">David describes it</a><span>:</span></p><blockquote st=
yle=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p styl=
e=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
; margin-left: 20px;"><em><span>The ultimate goal of writing online is to b=
uild a Personal Monopoly. It&#8217;s your </span><strong>unique intersectio=
n of skills, interests, and personality traits</strong><span> where you can=
 be known as the best thinker on a topic and open yourself up to the serend=
ipity that makes writing online so special.</span></em></p><p style=3D"colo=
r: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-=
left: 20px;"><em><strong>The Internet uniquely rewards people with Personal=
 Monopolies because it rewards differentiation.</strong></em></p></blockquo=
te><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: =
0 0 20px 0;"><span>When I started writing, I had no idea what my Personal M=
onopoly was. I knew that I was decent at and very curious about tech strate=
gy, but </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/943a7648-bdaf-4003-=
b2e5-36aea5d31172?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">B=
en Thompson</a><span> had already been writing </span><a href=3D"https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/90aa3cff-dd81-40d9-90bf-4f7b0c399469?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: =
#404040; text-decoration: underline;">Stratechery</a><span> for seven years=
 and was better at it than I could hope to be.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"=
color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><s=
pan>I tried a bunch of different things, like </span><a href=3D"https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/6eb7ee7c-a76e-41bd-8e4e-229cc76ddbb6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #=
404040; text-decoration: underline;">Philly Sports x Education x Internet</=
a><span>, but they didn&#8217;t quite work. Then I realized that most strat=
egy writing is very serious, and I&#8217;m not. What if I combined tech str=
ategy with pop culture and a dash of my own personality? The first time I h=
it on the intersection was in a piece called </span><em><a href=3D"https://=
substack.com/redirect/4f4a2ca0-4487-4046-b332-748b3d4a2a2a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color=
: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">Startup Economic Lessons From Shen =
Yun&#8217;s Empire</a></em><span>. It combined my experience at an on-deman=
d startup with a little bit of my economics degree and interest in strategy=
 with Shen Yun. It was a piece that Ben Thompson couldn&#8217;t, or at leas=
t wouldn&#8217;t, have written.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040;=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>When I star=
ted writing Not Boring full-time a year later, my first essays lived at the=
 intersection of tech strategy and pop culture: </span><em><a href=3D"https=
://substack.com/redirect/079c37f4-c6d9-437e-a504-045a67ba6fab?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"co=
lor: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">Jeff Bezos&#8217; Fashion Flex</=
a></em><span>, </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/94d04d7e=
-46ab-4766-9d5a-6ab3fdf7d4fd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: un=
derline;">Schumpeter&#8217;s Gale</a><span>,</span></em><span> </span><em><=
a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/7ac2b81c-dbeb-4110-94a8-1d715872867=
4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=
=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">Wackos and Zoom=
Gl&#252;ts</a></em><span>. The intersection forced me to differentiate, and=
 over time, as I&#8217;ve dropped the direct pop culture references, I&#821=
7;ve tried to maintain my unique, less serious voice.&#160;</span></p><p st=
yle=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;">Not Boring&#8217;s growth has been a result of that differentiation, a=
nd as more people write about startups with a lighter tone, one of my goals=
 in 2023 is to keep experimenting with ways to double-down on the uniquenes=
s.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>When I started writing, I thought that, if I wa=
s lucky, I&#8217;d be able to grow this to 5,000 subscribers and buy myself=
 time to find a next job that I really loved. I didn&#8217;t think I could =
build a real business off of the intersection of tech strategy and pop cult=
ure. My lesson here is that </span><strong>the internet rewards differentia=
tion in bigger ways than you can imagine before experiencing it</strong><sp=
an>.&#160;</span></p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-moz-=
osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; color=
