040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The whole con=
versation is worth listening to &#8211; I&#8217;d never heard of John befor=
e and I almost skipped it, but it was one of my favorite episodes in a whil=
e &#8211; but one line stuck out:</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>&#8220;The things th=
at are going to be valuable are the things you can&#8217;t teach or copy.&#=
8221;</strong><span>&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">This sounds almost obvious, =
and echoes Mr. Beast&#8217;s point, but it stands in direct opposition to t=
he way the system is currently set up. Humans spend the first twenty-two ye=
ars of our lives, and sometimes more, being taught and learning how to copy=
=2E Then we take more courses, learn best=
 practices, and apply them. Pre-Inte=
rnet, being average in a rich enough country was a safe way to ensure that =
you&#8217;d have a decent job and a middle class lifestyle, but the Interne=
t rewards differentiation with outsized rewards. Average is still employabl=
e, but the gap between average and differentiated keeps growing.&#160;&#160=
;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Average may not even be employable for long, though, a=
t least in knowledge work. </span><strong>AI is exceptional at average</str=
ong><span>. If something can be taught, it can learn it better. If it can b=
e copied, it can copy it faster.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040=
; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Of course, there=
&#8217;s a whole economy outside of knowledge work and a good argument to b=
e made for doing a job 9-5, getting paid, and spending the rest of your tim=
e with your family and friends. Service jobs aren&#8217;t going anywhere an=
y time soon. In fact, one of the biggest surprises in AI is that it&#8217;s=
 coming for knowledge workers first.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">But if you&#8217;re=
 reading this, I assume that you&#8217;re interested in the kind of work th=
at&#8217;s subject to the forces of differentiation. And for that kind of w=
ork, at some point in the near future, differentiation is going to be the o=
nly way to thrive.&#160;</p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=
=3D"-moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialias=
ed; color: #404040; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, Blink=
MacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Col=
or Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-we=
ight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relativ=
e;"><strong>Differentiation Is About to Get a Whole Lot More Important</str=
ong></h3><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0;">The third inspiration for this post was my conversation =
with Anton on the data on which AI models are trained:&#160;</p><a href=3D"=
https://substack.com/redirect/1f9ff5b9-9747-4845-8a2a-784ffe58634c?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" target=3D"_blan=
k" class=3D"youtube-wrap" style=3D"display: block; margin: 1.6em 0;"><img s=
rc=3D"https://substackcdn.com/image/youtube/w_550,c_limit/l_youtube_play_qy=
qt8q,w_120/eyH1Y7Q4kxY" style=3D"-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: n=
one !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; max-width: 10=
0%; vertical-align: middle; width: 100%;"></a><p style=3D"color: #404040; f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">I&#8217;d of course=
 like for you to watch the whole thing and subscribe, but I&#8217;ll give y=
ou the relevant takeaway here.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In the current stat=
e of the art, </span><strong>models are only as good as the data they&#8217=
;re trained on </strong><em><strong>and</strong></em><strong> the models ca=
n&#8217;t generate new training data themselves.</strong><span> AI-generate=
d output is based on the data that trained the AI in the first place, so an=
y data it creates will be a regurgitation of the data it already has. That =
means that humans will need to create fresh data by coming up with new idea=
s and new explanations of the world in order for the models to improve.&#16=
0;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">There&#8217;s a very clear way to see how this could=
 lead to a dystopian future in which the AI hires people to generate new ar=
t, music, and ideas to fill in the gaps in its understanding, but there&#82=
17;s also a much more hopeful way to view where this is heading.&#160;</p><=
p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 =
20px 0;"><strong>As the value of things you can teach or copy trends toward=
s zero, the value of fresh new ideas increases. </strong><span>&#160;</span=
></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">The stage is set for an era of fresh new ideas because the i=
ncentives have never been more tilted in their favor. This current internet=
 interstitial is just an appetizer.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Today, it&#821=
7;s so tantalizingly easy to copy others, to create undifferentiated produc=
ts or ideas in the pursuit of doing </span><em>something, </em><span>that i=
t&#8217;s become the default. Just as AI doesn&#8217;t improve with stale, =
rehashed data, the world doesn&#8217;t progress based upon stale, rehashed =
ideas. We progress, as we evolve, based on </span><strong>mutations</strong=
><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Siddhartha Mukherjee concludes his excel=
lent book, </span><em>The Gene: An Intimate History</em><span>, with an ack=
nowledgment of that fact: &#8220;We seek constancy in heredity &#8211; and =
find its opposite: variation. </span><strong>Mutants are necessary to maint=
ain the essence of ourselves.</strong><span>&#8221;&#160;</span></p><p styl=
e=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
;">The alpha is being squeezed out of doing the same things slightly better=
=2E You need to become a mutant.&#160;</p=
><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>A few minutes with =
ChatGPT, despite its flaws and shortcomings, will disavail you of the belie=
f that memorizing things just to memorize them will continue to be valuable=
=2E A few minutes with Replit&#8217;s Gho=
stwriter will do the same for your b=
elief in basic coding. Ditto for </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/red=
irect/47bd8d75-7d8d-48f6-bca4-a72117110474?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-=
decoration: underline;">Lex</a><span> and writing, or Stable Diffusion and =
drawing.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Memorize, code, write, and draw if you l=
ove doing those things, if getting your hands dirty helps you think better,=
 if you&#8217;re trying to earn your corpus of basic knowledge the hard way=
 so that you can jump off from a stable base, or if you want to do them dif=
ferently than anyone ever has; otherwise, don&#8217;t waste your time. It w=
ill regurgitate better than you ever could.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #40=
4040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The only ans=
wer is differentiation. Call it novelty, creativity, mutation.&#160;</p><p =
style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;">Follow curiosities down deep rabbit holes and emerge with unique ide=
as. Partake in vivid and varied adventures to build up a set of experiences=
 that is unique to you. Run away from the areas in which you are average an=
d towards those where you might be special. Start a company because the wor=
ld needs it, and because if you don&#8217;t start that specific company, no=
 one else will.</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">You don&#8217;t need to be the world&#8217;s b=
est brain surgeon; you might be the world&#8217;s fastest pumpkin carver. A=
nd when you find those areas where your curiosity, skills, and personality =
meet, lean in so hard that you create a Personal Monopoly no human or machi=
ne can touch.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The world will be a richer, more col=
orful place when more people are freed up to learn, create, and build novel=
 things that only they can. This might be technology&#8217;s greatest gift =
to humanity. </span><strong>By making the competition to be better at someo=
ne else&#8217;s game practically futile, it frees us up to play different g=
ames.&#160;</strong></p><div style=3D"font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;">=
